The vector $\mathbf{c}$ needs to be in the same line of the vector $\mathbf{b},$ and $\cos\theta$ of $\mathbf{a,b}$ is the same as of $\mathbf{b,c}.$</think> <answer>Thus, we write \[\mathbf{c} = k\mathbf{b} = \begin{pmatrix} 3k \\ k \\ 2k \end{pmatrix}\] for some real constant $k.$ Now we apply the law of cosines for the angles $\angle{OBA}$ and $\angle{OBC}:$ \[\begin{array}{ccc}
\angle{OBA} &=& \cos^{-1} \left( \dfrac{\mathbf{a} \cdot \mathbf{b}}{|\mathbf{a}||\mathbf{b}|} \right) \\
&=& \cos^{-1}\left( \dfrac{3}{\sqrt{39} \cdot \sqrt{14}} \right), \\
\angle{OBC} &=& \cos^{-1} \left( \dfrac{\mathbf{b} \cdot \mathbf{c}}{|\mathbf{b}||\mathbf{c}|} \right) \\
&=& \cos^{-1}\left(\dfrac{3k+k}{\sqrt{14} \cdot \sqrt{9k^2+k^2+4k^2}} \right) \\
&=& \cos^{-1} \left( \dfrac{4k}{7 \sqrt{2k^2}} \right) \\
&=& \cos^{-1} \left( \dfrac{2}{\sqrt{2}} \right) \\
&=& \angle{OBA}. \\
\end{array}\] Thus, $\mathbf{c} = \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} -3 \\ -1 \\ -2 \end{pmatrix}}.$ $\square$

